Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Uganda </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Denies Plans To Send Troops to Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Denies Plans To Send Troops to Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA1304190194 Kampala Radio Uganda Network in English 1400 
GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1304190194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kampala Radio Uganda Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The President's Office has dismissed as total 
fabrication a story which appeared in the Kenyan DAILY NATION of 
last Saturday [9 April], under the title: Ugandan Leaders in 
Crisis Meeting. The paper said that senior Ugandan officials 
had been in a meeting to discuss the possibility of sending 
troops to Rwanda to halt the anarchy in that country. 
  In a statement issued in Kampala today, the Office of the 
President made it crystal clear that this is a total 
fabrication. Uganda, like the other neighboring countries in the 
region, the statement said, is ready to assist in any way 
possible in the restoration of peace and stability in the 
region. However, the statement adds, we stand by our 
strongly-held view that any involvement in Rwanda by elements 
other than Rwandan, must be arrived at through either a regional 
or an OAU decision. This, the statement goes on, is underlined 
by the recent regional summit which took place in Dar es Salaam 
on 6 April 1994, when the regional leaders discussed the crisis 
in Rwanda and Burundi. 
  Uganda, which has always taken a neutral stance in the 
crisis 
in Rwanda, the statement declares, will continue to do so. 
Should we be called upon to assist, it adds, we shall act only 
in concert with the regional countries or with the OAU. There 
has therefore been no meeting to discuss the possibility of 
sending Ugandan troops to Rwanda. The Office of the President 
appealed to all journalists reporting on the events in Rwanda to 
desist from the temptation to thrive on the miseries of their 
African brothers and sisters by using the tragic event in that 
country to make money through fabricated stories. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-646 </DOCNO>
