<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNITA Reports Continued Clashes in Cuanza Norte </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNITA Reports Continued Clashes in Cuanza Norte </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1304200794 Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro in 
Portuguese 1900 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1304200794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Violent clashes are still taking place in Cuanza 
Norte Province where Popular Movement for the Liberation of 
Angola-Labor Party [MPLA-PT] troops are involved in an offensive 
against the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola 
[UNITA] for the control of N'Dalatando. The military offensive 
has already met its most difficult test near the Lucala 2 River 
bridge on the Dondo- N'Dalatando road. Sources from the Cuanza 
Norte Command [word indistinct] say that between 7 and 11 April 
our courageous soldiers destroyed an enemy military convoy and 
successfully blocked the repressive forces who were trying to 
advance toward the (Bimba) highlands. As a result, Armed Forces 
for the Liberation of Angola [FALA] combatants killed 57 MPLA 
elements, burned eight vehicles, including [words indistinct] 
tankers containing 6,000 liters of diesel, and captured four 
communication radios, 13 R-4 weapons, three PKM machine guns, 
countless rounds ammunitions of different calibers, as well as 
an assortment of war materiel. Seeing their plans to storm 
N'Dalatando thwarted, over the past few days the MPLA air force 
and artillery units stepped up attacks on civilian targets, 
killing innocent women, elderly people, and children. The 
gallant FALA combatants will continue to defend the people and 
their property [words indistinct]. 

</TEXT>

