<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Burundi </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Outlines Evacuation Plans From Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Outlines Evacuation Plans From Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA1304161594 Bujumbura Radio-Television Nationale du Burundi 
Radio in French 1100 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1304161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bujumbura Radio-Television Nationale du Burundi 
Radio </F>

<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The foreign minister, who was contacted this 
morning, has called on all Burundians in Kigali to gather if 
possible at the Burundian Embassy to await their imminent 
repatriation. According to a high-ranking official of the same 
ministry, negotiations on the repatriation of our compatriots 
from the Rwandan capital began last weekend. Those who were in 
Gisenyi have left Rwandan territory. There are around 40 people 
left. Two planes will leave Bujumbura soon for Goma, eastern 
Zaire, to where these people were evacuated. 
  A special flight is planned in the next few hours for those 
who are in Kigali and who are able to reach the Burundian 
Embassy. The high-ranking Foreign Ministry official told us 
that at the Burundian Embassy in Kigali, 30 Burundians are 
awaiting repatriation, and will receive French and Belgian 
military assistance. 
  Those who cannot easily reach the embassy are asked to join 
any Belgian or French citizens residing nearby to be evacuated 
with other expatriates. In case of problems, they can call the 
Burundian Embassy in Kigali on the following number: 75512. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

