<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-072 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Congo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police, Opposition Supporters Clash in Brazzaville </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police, Opposition Supporters Clash in Brazzaville </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1304121094 Paris AFP in French 0947 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1304121094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brazzaville, 13 Apr (AFP) -- A brief clash occurred 
this morning between some ministerial reserve policemen and 
opposition supporters close to former President Denis 
Sassou-Nguesso, in the eastern Brazzaville district of Mpila, 
according to witnesses. No details have emerged on the causes 
and outcome of this clash, which occurred near the former 
president's residence. The machine-gun fire had stopped by 
midmorning but there were still signs of tension in the area, an 
Army officer said. Defense Minister Raymond Damase Ngollo has 
held a meeting with members of the Army High Command and 
officers from the north of the country, who are close to General 
Sassou-Nguesso, to study ways and means of ending the clashes, 
the same officer added. 
  Security forces have been deployed in Mpila to check the 
activities of armed robbers, who have been attacking the goods 
trains of the Congo-Ocean railway company, the police said. 
Police presence has been stepped up since the death on 3 April 
of a soldier, who was killed by a stray bullet during a 
shoot-out between security forces and the "cobras," the nickname 
of Gen. Sassou- Nguesso's armed supporters. His supporters are 
opposed to the presence of the security forces in Mpila and fear 
that this could serve as a pretext to attack the residence of 
the former head of state, who is presently in his native 
village, Oyo, 600 km north of Brazzaville. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

