Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   Heavy Fighting Continues; UN Troops Begin Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Heavy Fighting Continues; UN Troops Begin Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    RPF Said To Hold Strategic Positions </H4>

<F P=102> EA1304141294 (Clandestine) Radio Muhabura in English to 
Rwanda 1100 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1304141294 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Radio Muhabura </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Following the bloody violence that claimed more than 
20,000 people in Kigali, including the prime minister, Madame 
Agathe Uwilingiyimana, and some of her cabinet ministers, some 
forces of the Rwandan Patriotic Front [RPF] have moved to Kigali 
in order to stop the massacre and establish law and order in the 
capital of Rwanda. 
  Latest reports from Kigali say that the Rwandan Patriotic 
Army [RPA] have captured some positions of strategic importance 
in Kigali. Fighting has also been going on between the RPA and 
the government forces in the northern part of Rwanda. The RPA 
has liberated Mutara zone completely. The government forces are 
now fleeing in disarray. In Byumba, the town is besieged by the 
RPA, ready to flush out the government forces but the operation 
has been halted by a request from the UNAMIR [UN Assistance 
Mission in Rwanda], who requested the RPA to hold fire so that 
the UNAMIR can evacuate its forces that are in Byumba. 
  The current offensive by the RPA in Kigali is primarily 
intended to reinforce the RPA forces in Kigali who have been 
under attack by the presidential guard. A representative of the 
UNAMIR has confirmed that the RPA forces from the north have now 
linked with the RPA battalion in Kigali and there is no sign of 
resistance from the Rwandan Government forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

