<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Heavy Fighting Continues; UN Troops Begin Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    French Troops Start To Leave </H4>

<F P=102> LD1304203194 Paris France-2 Television Network in French 
1800 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304203194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] In Rwanda, thousands of civilians are continuing 
to flee the massacres while the fighting between rebels and 
government forces appears to be escalating in the capital, 
Kigali. Today Cooperation Minister Michel Roussin confirmed the 
deaths of two French gendarmes and the wife of one of them to 
the National Assembly. Francois Leotard informed the senators 
of the departure late this afternoon of the last French company 
of soldiers. Before leaving Rwanda himself our special 
correspondent, Philippe Boisserie, sent us his report: 
  [Begin Boisserie recording] The French military are leaving 
Kigali at the same time as the Rwandan Patriotic Front are 
entering it. Operation Amaryllis, for the evacuation of 
foreigners, is ending. With 120 of his men, Colonel Poncet, who 
was leading the operation, left as night was falling, while all 
around the airport, the guns thundered. Only 50 French soldiers 
remain on the scene. Their mission is to support the Belgian and 
Italian soldiers in recovering their nationals who are still 
trapped in the four corners of the country. The two warring 
sides have promised to allow these operations to go ahead, the 
only condition being that everyone should be out within 48 hours. 
  The Rwandans are thus going to settle their scores among 
themselves, and it appears that the Tutsi minority of the Rwanda 
Patriotic Front are in the process of taking power. [passage 
omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

