<H3> <TI>   HCR-PT States New Conditions for Premier Appointment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    HCR-PT States New Conditions for Premier Appointment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1304135594 Paris AFP in French 1921 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1304135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kinshasa, 12 Apr (AFP) -- The future prime minister 
to be designated by the radical opposition must first sign the 
protocol agreement reached in January between the presidential 
group and the opposition and the special arrangement concerning 
the number of portfolios to be assigned to each political 
family, a statement issued by the bureau of the High Council of 
the Republic-Transitional Parliament (HCR-PT) indicated. These 
agreements between the presidential group and the opposition 
were reached after four months of negotiations at the Palais du 
Peuple in Kinshasa. 
  The HCR-PT bureau also underlined that the application for 
the post of prime minister should include among others the 
minutes and general report on consultations with the Sacred 
Union and its allies, and a report on consultations with the 
presidential group duly signed by all the parties concerned. 
  It may be recalled that Etienne Tshisekedi's party, the 
Union 
for Democracy and Social Progress, which participated in the 
Palais du Peuple negotiations, did not sign the protocol 
agreement due to differences over the appointment of the head of 
government. Under the transitional constitutional law 
promulgated on 9 April, a prime minister should be appointed 
between 9 and 20 April. 

</TEXT>

