<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mediation Efforts `Collapse' Over Preconditions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mediation Efforts `Collapse' Over Preconditions </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    IFP Officials Meet in Johannesburg </H4>

<F P=102> MB1404083394 Johannesburg SAPA in Engligh 0802 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1404083394 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  Engligh </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg April 14 SAPA -- Inkatha Freedom Party 
[IFP] officials were meeting at a Johannesburg hotel Thursday 
[14 April] morning amid continuing uncertainty about the 
international mediation process. 
  The process was meant to start on Wednesday morning but was 
delayed because of a dispute over the terms of reference for 
mediation. The dispute arose from the IFP's objection to a 
reference to the election date in the new terms of reference 
drawn up after the government joined the process as a full 
participant. 
  The IFP has argued that agreement on constitutional issues 
would lead inevitably to negotiations on a new election date, a 
position rejected by both the government and the African 
National Congress. 
  A spokesman for the international mediators said they had 
held discussions with the parties and were preparing to release 
a statement during the course of the morning. 
  A draft agreement between the government, the African 
National Congress and the IFP was reached after talks in 
Pretoria involving representatives of the three parties. The 
agreement suggested a two- phase approach to mediation whose 
effect would be to separate the question of the election date 
from the terms of reference. 
  The draft agreement was discussed with the mediators at a 
meeting late on Wednesday night. However, the draft was awaiting 
the final approaval of the IFP before the mediation began. 

</TEXT>

