<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mediation Efforts `Collapse' Over Preconditions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mediation Efforts `Collapse' Over Preconditions </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Mediators Find `Insurmountable Problems' </H4>

<F P=102> MB1404103994 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1032 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1404103994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg April 14 SAPA -- The international 
mediation effort has struck "insurmountable problems," 
Constitutional Development Minister Roelf Meyer said on Thursday 
[14 April] after meeting mediator Henry Kissinger. 
  Mr Meyer said that as far as government was concerned the 
mediation could continue, but the problems surrounding the terms 
of reference "will cause this current effort not to continue". 
  Asked whether the mediation, which was intended to resolve 
outstanding constitutional difficulties between the African 
National Congress and the Inkatha Freedom Party would be 
abandoned, Mr Meyer said: "On the basis of them accepting that 
there is no clarity on the terms of refence that is 
unfortunately the position". 
  Mr Meyer said the divisive issue was not which particular 
terms of reference would be used by the mediators, but the issue 
of the election date. 
  He said the ANC believed there was no linkage between the 
election date and mediation, while the IFP [Inkatha Freedom 
Party] argued that there was a linkage. 
  He said government's position was that the elections should 
go ahead as scheduled. 
  The mediators were due to address the media at 1PM on their 
plans. 
  IFP negotiator Ben Ngubane said he was still hopeful that 
the 
mediation could go ahead. Another IFP negotiator said government 
was prepared to go back to the original terms of reference that 
did not mention the election date but that this still had to be 
cleared with the ANC. 
  ANC Secretary General Cyril Ramaphosa was due to meet the 
mediators at Thursday lunchtime. 
  However, Mr Meyer said the issue was not what document was 
used but how mediation would affect the election date. "The 
election date is fixed and we are proceeding on that basis," he 
said. 
  He said it was "very unfortunate" that the mediators had 
come 
to South Africa when there was no agreement on the terms of 
reference. He said Dr Kissinger had taken the "correct position" 
in saying that the mediation did not include negotiations on the 
election date. 
  He said the government was still prepared to involve itself 
in mediation and in other attempts to resolve problems with the 
IFP and with the Zulu king. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-681 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr072_c_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-072 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mediation Efforts `Collapse' Over Preconditions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mediation Efforts `Collapse' Over Preconditions </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Mediation Effort Fails </H4>

<F P=102> MB1404114794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1133 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1404114794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg April 14 SAPA -- The international 
mediation process collapsed in disarray on Thursday [14 April] 
afternoon with the mediatiors saying they could not continue 
without agreement on the terms of reference. 
  Mediator Dr Henry Kissinger said the mediators had dropped 
everything to come to South Africa on the understanding that the 
parties had agreed to the terms of reference. "We met the 
parties but made no proposals because our mediation could begin 
only after the terms of reference had been agreed. 
  "I wish the parties all the best," Dr Kissinger told a media 
briefing. 
  The mediation collapsed in spite of intense efforts 
involving the ANC, Inkatha Freedom Party and government 
negotiators to agree on the terms of reference. 
  The dispute arose from the IFP's insistence that the 
election 
date be part of the mediation process. 
  Another mediator, former British Foreign Secretary Lord 
Carrington said the mediators had not thought that they would 
have an easy task. "The fact that it has failed fills me with 
sadness," Lord Carrington said. 
  Dr Kissinger said the mediators understood that it would be 
difficult for the parties to resolve historic differences in 
such a short period. He said the mediators had urged the parties 
to see whether they could bridge the gaps between themselves. 
  Dr Kissinger said the terms of reference had been faxed to 
him on Sunday, which reflected agreement among the parties. 
  "When we came here we found that the terms of reference had 
either been reopened or were not fully agreed as we had 
understood." 
  The mediation was to have begun on Tuesday morning. The 
seven 
mediators were now making arrangements to leave the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

