<H3> <TI>   Police Confirm Probe Into Mercenaries in Angola </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Confirm Probe Into Mercenaries in Angola </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1304114394 Pretoria Radio Pretoria in Afrikaans 1700 GMT 
12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1304114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pretoria Radio Pretoria </F>
<F P=105>  Afrikaans </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A police spokesman confirmed that the police have 
investigated allegations of mercenaries from the South African 
Defense Force [SADF] being involved in military activities in 
Angola. 
  A spokesman of the SADF, Colonel John Rolf, said it was 
being 
alleged that in cases where South African soldiers were acting 
as mercenaries in violation of the defense law, justice had to 
take its course. After the police have completed their 
investigation, the attorney general will have to decide whether 
prosecution will be instituted. Col. Rolf denied that the South 
African soldiers were involved in Angola with the full knowledge 
and consent of the SADF; also that the companies responsible for 
sending soldiers to Angola, Executive Outcomes, were a front for 
the SADF. 
  The police spokesman in turn said that there has been a 
police investigation into the allegations after the commissioner 
of police had requested the investigation. According to 
reports, there are still about 500 South African soldiers in 
Angola. These soldiers are fighting on the side of the Marxist 
MPLA [Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola] troops. 

</TEXT>

