<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mediation Efforts `Collapse' Over Preconditions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mediation Efforts `Collapse' Over Preconditions </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Negotiators Present Proposal </H4>

<F P=102> MB1304181494 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1751 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1304181494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Patrick Bulger] </F>
  [Text] Pretoria April 13 SAPA -- Government, African 
National Congress and Inkatha Freedom Party [IFP] negotiating 
teams emerged from nearly five hours of talks in Pretoria on 
Wednesday [13 April] night to say they had a new proposal to 
save the international mediation process. 
  The process broke down before it began on Wednesday morning 
when IFP leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi rejected the terms of 
reference. 
  ANC Secretary General Cyril Ramaphosa said after the 
Pretoria 
talks the IFP still wanted to engage the ANC in negotiations on 
a new date for elections. He said a change of date was 
impossible and it was not on the table for mediation. "That 
date is sacrosanct and is not the subject of mediation," Mr 
Ramaphosa said. 
  He left the talks for a meeting in Johannesburg with 
mediators Dr Henry Kissinger and Lord Peter Carrington. 
  Mr Ramaphosa said the negotiators had agreed in principle on 
dividing the mediation process into two phases. The first would 
be a pre-mediation agreement and the second an agreement on the 
implementation of the results of mediation. 
  Minister of Home Affairs Danie Schutte said government did 
not favour changing the election date. "The very last thing we 
would want to extend is the election date," Mr Schutte said. He 
said the proposal put together by the negotiators appeared to be 
acceptable to all the parties 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

