<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Congo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Calm Returns to Mpila After Police, Opposition Clash </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Calm Returns to Mpila After Police, Opposition Clash </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1404185494 Paris AFP in French 1311 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1404185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brazzaville, 14 Apr (AFP) -- Calm has returned this 
morning to the eastern Brazzaville industrial district of Mpila, 
where a brief clash occurred yesterday between opposition 
supporters and security forces. Traffic has resumed in the 
area, where businesses had remained closed yesterday because of 
the prevailing tension after an exchange of gunfire. No 
gunshots have been heard by journalists. This return to 
normalcy follows President Pascal Lissouba's message warning all 
Army and police officers against any act that "would jeopardize 
the peace process and the security of people and property." 
  Former President Denis Sassou-Nguesso's supporters are 
opposed to the deployment of security forces in the district, 
fearing that this could serve as a pretext to attack the 
residence of the former head of state, who has been living for 
several months now in his native village, Oyo, 600 km north of 
Brazzaville. According to the police, the security forces were 
deployed in Mpila to check the activities of armed robbers, who 
have been attacking goods trains. 

</TEXT>

