<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-073 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Congo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Dismisses Chief Treasurer </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Dismisses Chief Treasurer </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0804163194 Paris AFP in French 1233 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0804163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brazzaville, 8 Apr (AFP) -- Congolese radio 
announced today that Paulin Ayina, the chief treasurer of Congo 
(director of the Treasury), was dismissed yesterday by Prime 
Minister Jacques Joachim Yhombi Opango. 
  He was replaced by a principal inspector of the Treasury, 
Mampassi Tsika, the radio added, without giving the reasons for 
the dismissal. 
  A senior civil servant close to the Congolese Presidency 
told 
AFP that the government accused Mr. Ayina of the "centralization 
of power and an absence of transparency in his activities." 
  The public treasury collects about 7 billion CFA francs (70 
million French francs) every month, representing regular income 
and oil royalties for the Congo. 
  Several trade unions have recently denounced the poor 
management of state incomes and the abusive expenses of public 
treasury funds. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

