<H3> <TI>   Signs of Trench Warfare Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Signs of Trench Warfare Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504103394 Paris Radio France International in French 0630 
GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1504103394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] In Rwanda, the Rwandan Patriotic Front [RPF] 
radio station has warned that, after midnight, foreign troops or 
aircraft entering the country are likely to be considered as 
hostile. [passage omitted] 
  In the streets of Kigali there is already talk of trench 
warfare, something seen on the front line by Jean Helene: 
  [Helene] Boulevard Umugamba has become a veritable front 
line: 200 meters from the airport, controlled by the government 
army, is the RPF's first barrier, and from this point on, along 
the lower lefthand side of the boulevard, runs a very long 
trench holding several dozen RPF fighters, who have positioned 
heavy machine guns in firing positions at regular intervals 
along it. Even when escorted by UN vehicles you must not hang 
about here, because bullets sometimes whistle past all around 
you. On the left is the former rebels' billet, which today is 
the core of the pocket of resistance taken by the RPF in the 
northeast section of the capital. To the right, just below the 
hill, extends a vast no-man's land, where its commandos venture 
out. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

