<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Rejection of Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Rejection of Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA1404214794 (Clandestine) Radio Muhabura in French to 
Rwanda 1815 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1404214794 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Radio Muhabura </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Rwandan Patriotic Front [RPF] combatants are 
continuing with their armed fight against elements of the 
Presidential Guard, as well as government soldiers who decided 
to join the criminals. The fighting is centered in the capital, 
where the Presidential Guard continues to massacre innocent 
people, after being prompted by the pretext of President 
Habyarimana's death in an plane crash. 
  The information broadcast this morning by several foreign 
radio stations and on Kigali radio concerning truce negotiations 
between the RPF and the transitional government put in place by 
those who organized the massacres is baseless. (Jean-Baptiste 
Kades) has this report: 
  [(Kades)] Yes, [words indistinct] since this morning, 
several 
international news media have reported that the RPF agreed to 
meet the self-proclaimed authorities in Kigali, in order to 
discuss a possible cease-fire. The RPF insists on informing 
Rwandan and international opinion that this information is 
baseless. There is no question of the RPF holding any 
negotiations whatsoever with this pseudo-government while the 
killers working for certain government members now based in 
Gitarama continue to kill all over the country. 
  We repeat: There will be no dealings whatsoever between the 
RPF and this government. The only consultations which have 
taken place in Kigali are, to the best of our knowledge, between 
the executive committees of political parties involved in the 
Arusha peace agreements. The members of these executive 
committees, or at least those of them who have escaped the 
massacres organized by the Presidential Guards, the Coalition 
for the Defense of the Republic [words indistinct] of the 
Republican National Movement for Democracy and Development, met 
today in Kigali to discuss the situation now prevailing in the 
country. This has nothing to do with any form of cease-fire. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

