Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Officers Killed in Clashes Near N'Dalatando </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army Officers Killed in Clashes Near N'Dalatando </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1404195994 Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro in 
Portuguese 1900 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1404195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Cuanza Norte the Luanda government is trying to 
storm N'Dalatando. Our correspondent Morais Abel reports: 
  In a vain attempt to cross Lucala 2 River, a number of 
clashes have taken place, particularly one in which the enemy 
lost a number of senior officers, including Colonel Chico Cuma, 
chief of the General Staff of the 45th Regiment, Lieutenant 
Colonel Neto, commander of that regiment's 1st Battalion, and a 
captain in charge of the tank company. 
  Two battalions of special forces, which the Popular Movement 
for the Liberation of Angola [MPLA] regards as the most powerful 
units involved in the ongoing offensive, have been put to 
flight. The two battalions suffered (?17) killed, including a 
lieutenant and three noncommissioned officers. Our forces 
captured 14 AK47's, and assorted ammunition. Noncommissioned 
officer Carlos Antonio Congumi, a member of the Luanda garrison 
command and born in Cuanza Sul, was taken prisoner during a 
clash. He revealed secret information which has helped Armed 
Forces for the Liberation of Angola combatants in their 
defensive operations [words indistinct] on the Luanda-Dondo and 
Dondo-Dange-ia-Menha roads, which are used as supply lines for 
the MPLA. 
  Enemy commanders and soldiers have become frustrated in view 
of systematic desertions and embezzlement of supplies [words 
indistinct]. On 10 April 87 members of the operational 
commandos fled, one of whom was captured by our forces. The 
others headed to their homes. 

</TEXT>

