<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNITA Radio Reports on Fighting in Bie, Elsewhere </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNITA Radio Reports on Fighting in Bie, Elsewhere </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1404200694 Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro in 
Portuguese 1900 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1404200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 12 April Popular Movement for the Liberation of 
Angola-Labor Party [MPLA-PT] aircraft bombed Quirima in yet 
another attack on the armed forces of the National Union for the 
Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] for having tightened their 
siege on (?Malange) to ensure the success of relief operations. 
A source with the General Staff of the Armed Forces for the 
Liberation of Angola [FALA] says the bombing was carried out at 
1045, resulting in two dead and four seriously wounded. The 
dead include 78-year-old Antonio Jose Capando and a two-year-old 
child. 
  Meanwhile, clashes were reported in Bie yesterday. It all 
began when an MPLA-PT air force plane overflew UNITA defense 
lines and parachuted lethal equipment. Military sources say 
that once government troops realized that the supplies had 
fallen beyond their positions, they used force to try to break 
through UNITA lines. 
  FALA forces stationed in Bie are instructed not to react to 
any provocation, but had to take action in view of the threat 
posed by the advancing troops of Brigadier Simeone. Fire was 
exchanged for over three hours. The government army suffered at 
least 15 killed and an unspecified number of wounded. 
  It is believed that a number of civilians have been killed 
because of clashes in a residential area. FALA's command in the 
city of Bie regret the occurrence and has warned Luanda to 
desist from overflying the city of Bie with its air force. 
Today the situation returned to normal and the residents were 
able to go about their lives. 

</TEXT>

