<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Lesotho </F>
<H3> <TI>   Details of Maseru Military Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Details of Maseru Military Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1504075794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0744 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1504075794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Jonathon Rees] </F>
  [Text] Maseru April 15 SAPA -- Troops from the Royal 
Defence Force occupied a stragtegic hill overlooking the Lesotho 
capital of Maseru on Friday [15 April] morning, Information and 
Broadcasting Permanent Secretary Seeiso Sarutla said. This was 
apparently a bid to stop soldiers from the Makoanyane barracks 
from coming into town. 
  It was soldiers from Makoanyane who held four cabinet 
ministers hostage on Thursday after Deputy Prime Minister Sello 
Metsi Baholo was shot dead in a bid by soldiers from a section 
of Lesotho's Army to storm his house, Mr Sarutla said. 
  Automatic rifle fire was heard from the hill early Friday 
morning, but Maseru was otherwise calm and residents appeared to 
be going about normal business. 
  Prime Minister Itsu Mokhehle was scheduled to address 
Lesotho's Parliament and Senate on Friday morning. 
  Mr Sarutla said Thursday's killing and kidnapping could be 
an 
attempt to separate the prime minister from his cabinet and so 
render him ineffective. He said Lesotho's one year-old 
government under the Basotho Congress Party was still looking 
for clarity on long-standing pay demands from the military, but 
was determined not to give soldiers any increases above those 
received by other civil servants. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-741 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr073_d_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-073 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Lesotho </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1504093094 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0920 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1504093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Maseru April 15 SAPA -- The uprising in Lesotho 
appeared to be over on Friday [15 April] and South Africans were 
advised that it was again safe to visit Maseru, SABC [South 
African Broadcasting Corporation] radio news reported. South 
Africa's Ambassador to Lesotho Gerhard Visser said it was no 
longer dangerous to visit the Lesotho capital, where a minister 
was shot dead and four others were kidnapped on Thursday. 
  Troops occupied a hill overlooking Maseru on Friday morning 
and sporadic rifle fire was heard, but the city was otherwise 
calm. 
  The reason for Thursday's revolt could not yet be 
determined, 
but it was reported the soldiers who took part in the 
insurrection bore a grudge against Deputy Prime Minister 
Selometsi Baholo, who was killed on Thursday, and Justice 
Minister Kelebone Maope. 
  The two ministers earlier this year took part in talks at 
which rationalisation of the Lesotho Defence Force was 
recommended. 

</TEXT>

