<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Niger </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fundamentalists Reportedly Begin To Surrender </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fundamentalists Reportedly Begin To Surrender </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1404204794 Paris AFP in French 1313 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1404204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Niamey, 14 Apr (AFP) -- Muslim fundamentalists who 
took refuge in Kolouka after occupying the neighboring town of 
Bani Bangou, (180 km to the north of Niamey), began to surrender 
at midday today, Niger Interior Minister Ousmane Oumarou told 
AFP. 
  A detachment of the Nigerian Army encircled the village in 
the early hours of the morning and threatened to attack if the 
fundamentalists, who are members of the Izala sect, did not 
surrender. 
  On 11 and 12 March, clashes between members of the sect and 
security forces left 10 dead at Kolouka. The fundamentalists 
succeeded in leaving Bani Bangou during the evening of 12 March 
to return to their village. 

</TEXT>

