<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   France Denies Rumors Over Exercises With Benin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    France Denies Rumors Over Exercises With Benin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1404203194 Dakar PANA in English 1746 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1404203194 </F>
<F P=104>  Dakar PANA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, 14 Apr (PANA) -- France denied Thursday [14 
April] in Lagos that the recent joint military exercise it held 
with Benin, Nigeria's western neighbour, was aimed at 
intimidating Nigeria in the event of an out-break of hostilities 
with Cameroon over the disputed Bakassi Peninsula. 
  French defence attache in Nigeria, Col. John Eglinger, said 
that the exercise was planned "about a year ago," long before 
the current disagreement between Nigeria and Cameroon. Col. 
Eglinger said that Nigeria had been duly informed about the 
plans for holding the joint exercise. Concerning France's 
position in the Bakassi dispute between Nigeria and its former 
colony of Cameroon, englinger said that France was committed to 
""an amicable resolution"" of the conflict. He reiterated 
France's preparedness to assist mediate in the dispute which, he 
said, France believed could be resolved through "bilateral 
discussion." 
  France held its military exercise with Benin in March, an 
operation interpreted by military sources in the Nigerian 
capital as an effort to intimidate the Nigerian Army should the 
dispute over the oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula escalate into a 
military confrontation between Nigeria and Cameroon. France had 
allegedly used an unusually "large" arsenal including war planes 
and war ships in the exercise which lasted for several days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

