<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Togo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Koffigoh Vows To Hand Over Authority to New Premier </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Koffigoh Vows To Hand Over Authority to New Premier </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1404185094 Lome Radio Lome in French 0600 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1404185094 </F>
<F P=104>  Lome Radio Lome </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Prime Minister Joseph Kokou Koffigoh; issued </F>
in Lome on 13 April -- read by announcer] 
  [Text] In view of the persisting political impasse in the 
country and the confusion created following statements made by 
certain political leaders, Prime Minister Joseph Kokou Koffigoh 
wants to make the following clarifications: 
  1. The outgoing prime minister tendered in his resignation 
and that of his government on 21 March. The head of state 
accepted the resignation and asked the prime minister to 
continue conducting the daily affairs of state, which he has 
been doing to date, to ensure continuity. 
  2. Like every Togolese, the prime minister deplored and 
continues to deplore the difficulties the parliamentary majority 
parties are encountering in agreeing on the appointment of a new 
prime minister because this state of affairs is thwarting the 
establishment of the new institutions that are much desired by 
all. 
  3. It is proper to recall here the position of the 
government which refrained from interfering in the electoral 
disputes, in its concern for the absolute respect for the 
Electoral Law. In fact, Article 189 of the Electoral Law 
stipulates the following: Should the Supreme Court notice 
serious irregularities in the elections that might taint their 
sincerity and affect the global results, the court can annul the 
elections. The government would then fix the date for new 
elections which would take place within a month, at the latest, 
after the date on which the Supreme Court announces its 
decision. Clearly Togolese should know that it is not the 
government that annuls elections. However, the government is 
bound, in all circumstances, to respect the Electoral Law by 
fixing a date for the new elections. 
  4. Consequently, Prime Minister Joseph Koffigoh wants to 
inform the concerned political leaders that as soon as they find 
a prime minister, he is ready at all times to hand over the 
baton of office to him. 
  5. After all the sacrifices made with the people, Prime 
Minister Joseph Kokou Koffigoh reaffirms his faith in democracy 
in Togo. He, however, refuses to play the role of a scapegoat. 
  Prime Minister Koffigoh also appeals to the parliamentary 
majority party leaders to reach an agreement and to announce the 
outcome of their consultations in the superior interest of the 
Togolese people who have suffered far too much from demagogy and 
partisan squabbles. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

