  Deployment of both international and domestic observers is 
being concentrated in the Natal/kwaZulu area, the rural areas 
and the so-called no-go areas. 
<H5>  Domestic observer organisations </H5>
  The following domestic observer organisations have been 
accredited by the monitoring directorate of the IEC [Independent 
Electoral Commission]. Applications for accreditation expired 
on 27.03.1994. Figures for these organisations will be released 
later. 
1. Vonk 
  2. South African Catholic Bishops' Conference 
  3. The Methodist Church of South Africa 
  4. National Association of Democratic Lawyers (Nadel) 
  5. South African Council of Churches 
  6. National Electoral Observer Network in South Africa 
(NEON). 
  7. Pietermaritzburg Agency for Christian Social Awareness. 
  8. Accord. 
  9. Black Sash 
  10. Western Transvaal Education Foundation. 
  11. Islamic Business Corporation LTD. 
  12. Rotary International 
  13. Project Vote 
  14. Cosatu [Congress of South African Trade Unions] 
  15. CDR Network 
  16. Konrad Adenauer Foundation 
  17. Eldorado Park Advice Centre 
  18. King Williams Town Education and Information Trust 
  19. National Council of Women of South Africa 
  20. Zamdela Ministeri's Association 
  21. Community Law Centre 
  22. IDASA [Institute for a Democratic Alternative for South 
Africa] 
  23. National Council of Trade Unions 
  24. Umfundo Rural Education Project 
  25. Christian Women's Movement. 
  26. Church of the Province of Southern Africa 
  A maximum of three observers will be deployed at each voting 
station. 
  Both domestic (local) and international observers will have 
two full days of IEC training. International observers will be 
able to attend sessions at national office on the 19-20 April or 
on the 20-21, or 22-23 at a regional office. Domestic observers 
will be able to attend either of the latter two training 
sessions. All training sessions will cover the same material. 
  Additional training of international observers takes place 
in 
their home country by their organisation. The IEC has provided 
the (sample) training manual and handbook to registered overseas 
organisations. 
  It should be noted that, unlike monitors, observers have no 
intervention powers. They are not employees of the IEC and make 
their reports to their accredited organisations. These 
organisations then report to the IEC. 
  Liaison between international and domestic observers will be 
overseen by the monitoring directorate; a close relationship is 
expected. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

